  "title": "Rituals",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "2f8eca185119231d",
      "text": "One can understand *rituals* from the point of view of curtailing (*Coupieren*)  all approaches to reflexive communication. Communication is stiffened as a fixed process, and its rigidity itself takes the place of asking why this is so. The elements of the process and their order are fixed irrevocably, words are treated like things, the present counts and is not correctable either with regard to the future or on the basis of past experiences accrued in each case. The risk of using [[Symbol]]s is kept as low as possible. Rituals are comparable to the unquestioning self-evident facts of everyday life, which also eliminate reflexivity.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8953b973b4b25611",
      "text": "p. 613n34 That rituals represent a code for communication that is restricted and rendered without alternatives is a now common thesis. Cf. Mary Douglas, Natural Symbols: Explorations in Cosmology, London 1970; Roy A. Rappaport, The Sacred in Human Evolution, Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics 2 (1971), pp. 23-44; the same, Ritual, Sanctity and Cybernetics, American Anthropologist 73 (1971), pp. 59-76; Maurice Bloch, Symbols, Song, Dance and Features of Articulation: Is Religion an Extreme Form of Traditiohal Authority? European Archives of Sociology 15 (1974), pp. 55-81. It concerns, first of all, the cutting off of customary sensory references par excellence. This includes the curtailing (*Coupieren*) of reflexivity."
